        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden p-5 text-sm text-slate-350 border-t border-slate-850 bg-slate-950/20 leading-relaxed">
          Drawing optical illusions requires understanding how the visual system interprets flat lines as 3D structures. To begin drawing, you must carefully outline visual guides and grid boundaries. The brain determines depth from lighting cues, perspective angles, and line intersections. By sketching overlapping shapes or grid matrices, you create spatial patterns that exploit top-down predictions in the visual cortex. Fine-lining with dark ink and using pencil shading (from light gray to rich black gradients) reinforces these cues. These gradients manipulate the brain's luminance and depth perception, tricking it into seeing three-dimensional forms on a completely flat sheet of paper.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ 2 -->
      <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/40">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full p-5 text-left font-bold text-white flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-slate-900 transition-colors">
          <span>How to draw optical illusions step by step?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon text-purple-400 transition-transform">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden p-5 text-sm text-slate-350 border-t border-slate-850 bg-slate-950/20 leading-relaxed">
          To draw optical illusions step by step, you must follow a methodical geometric approach. First, sketch light guidelines using a hard pencil, which allows you to establish the isometric coordinates or geometric grids necessary for perspective distortion. Second, define the primary structure, such as intersecting lines or concentric shapes, ensuring perfect alignment. Third, add impossible joints or high-contrast borders that conflict with the layout. Fourth, apply shading gradients; standard graphite pencils are perfect for creating soft transitions that simulate curves or depth. Finally, trace the outer boundaries with black ink, erase the light guidelines, and verify the visual trick.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ 3 -->
      <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/40">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full p-5 text-left font-bold text-white flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-slate-900 transition-colors">
          <span>How to draw optical illusions easy?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon text-purple-400 transition-transform">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden p-5 text-sm text-slate-350 border-t border-slate-850 bg-slate-950/20 leading-relaxed">
          The easiest way to draw optical illusions is to start with shading-based or wireframe designs that do not require complex calculations. The classic Necker Cube is a perfect choice, created by drawing two overlapping squares and connecting their corresponding corners. Another simple project is the 3D Hole, which uses horizontal lines that bend into curves across a central oval to suggest a deep chasm. By leaving a slight gap between the object and its shadow, you can also easily simulate floating or levitation. These basic geometries rely on simple visual cues that are easy to sketch but highly effective at tricking the brain.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ 4 -->
      <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/40">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full p-5 text-left font-bold text-white flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-slate-900 transition-colors">
          <span>How to draw moving optical illusions?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon text-purple-400 transition-transform">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden p-5 text-sm text-slate-350 border-t border-slate-850 bg-slate-950/20 leading-relaxed">
          Drawing moving optical illusions requires combining high-frequency contrast boundaries and offset alignment shapes. To achieve a peripheral drift effect on paper, you must draw repeating sequences of colored blocks (such as white, light gray, black, and dark blue) in a grid or wheel pattern. Because the photoreceptors in the retina process high-contrast boundaries faster than low-contrast boundaries, a slight processing lag occurs in the visual cortex. When you scan your eyes across these repeating patterns, this timing difference is interpreted by direction-selective neurons in visual area V5/MT as actual physical motion, making the static drawing appear to bend, slide, or spin.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ 5 -->
      <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/40">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full p-5 text-left font-bold text-white flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-slate-900 transition-colors">
          <span>How to make optical illusions?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon text-purple-400 transition-transform">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden p-5 text-sm text-slate-350 border-t border-slate-850 bg-slate-950/20 leading-relaxed">
          Making optical illusions involves setting up visual conditions that trigger contradictory hypotheses in the brain. Start by choosing a specific mechanism, such as size constancy, lateral inhibition, or Gestalt closure. For example, to make a size illusion like the Delboeuf circles, draw two identical circles and surround one with a large ring and the other with a small ring. The surrounding context forces the visual cortex to scale the inner circles differently. Using high-contrast patterns, precise rulers, and geometric compasses ensures that the physical dimensions are mathematically exact, which is critical for the visual cortex to experience maximum cognitive friction and perceive the illusion.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ 6 -->
      <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/40">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full p-5 text-left font-bold text-white flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-slate-900 transition-colors">
          <span>How to create optical illusions?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon text-purple-400 transition-transform">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden p-5 text-sm text-slate-350 border-t border-slate-850 bg-slate-950/20 leading-relaxed">
          Creating optical illusions combines artistic design with the science of visual neuroscience. When you layout an illusion, you are intentionally programming sensory inputs to exploit evolutionary shortcuts in human sight. The brain constantly projects top-down predictions to construct the world around us. By using perspective lines that converge at false vanishing points, or by placing alternating high-contrast wedges, you can trigger specific errors in the visual pathway (from the retina to area V1 and V5). Rulers, mathematical grids, and high-contrast color transitions are the key tools needed to create these visual discrepancies, ensuring the brain resolves the geometry incorrectly.
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>

